<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-31T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-31T12:00:00-05:00" n="9" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d9">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee (Arms)/88:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the American Delegate</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-31T12:00:00-05:00">January 31, 1935—noon</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>468. Your No. 969, January 29, 5 p.m. It was our understanding that
                                the amendment of Category V, as suggested in the instruction of
                                December 24,<note n="26" xml:id="d9fn26">
                                    <ref target="frus1934v01#pg_211">
                                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1934, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 211</ref>.</note> taken in
                                conjunction with the amended text of Article 30 (<hi rend="italic">e</hi>) authorized in that instruction provided for the
                                inspection on the spot for production of civil aviation material for
                                which the French contend. Do the French desire something more than
                                this? If so, please submit by telegram, for my consideration, such
                                modifications of the present text of the Draft Articles as would be
                                necessary to carry out their ideas.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>